    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblins! You say? You didn't mention any goblins? Well, that's like asking a goblin if he prefers moss or shiny spoons—it's just *there*, you see! They're in the air, like the faint smell of stale swamp mushrooms.\n\nBack to your fabric, yes, if the weave is too tight and it restricts airflow, you are absolutely right to worry about heat retention. It's a direct consequence, much like if you try to herd a swarm of tiny, irritable goblins into a space too small—they get agitated, and the heat builds up! A denser weave traps more of the ambient heat, which is exactly what you don't want when your customers are trying to sleep comfortably in the summer. They'll feel that stuffiness, and those complaints will pile up faster than a goblin's pile of stolen shiny trinkets.\n\nTo mitigate this, even with a higher thread count, you need to look at the *weave structure* itself. A very tight plain weave might be suffocating, but a slightly looser twill or sateen weave, even with a high count, can manage to create those necessary micro-channels for air movement. It'",
